																		So,
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/technician-downs" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1399495); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1399495&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204947" alt="Technician Downs" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1399495)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/technician-downs" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1399495); return false;" >Technician Downs</a></span> <span class="odate time_1452133663 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">07 Jan 2016 02:27</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2435610">
									

<p>Casefile for Simferopol.</p>
<p>There isn't much in the way of narrative in this, I admit. It's more an exploration of format, and the question: <em>how does conflict affect Foundation containment operations?</em></p>
<p>Inherently, it's a dangerous topic. It's 2016, but the ceasefire in Ukraine is tentative, thousands have died, controversy still rages on who is &quot;really&quot; to blame for it all, but that's all secondary for the purposes of this tale. I've attempted to treat the subject as neutrally as possible.</p>
<p>GRU Division P has been rebranded as a division of the FSB for the purposes of this tale, to differentiate contemporary Russia from the Soviet Union.</p>
<p>Hopefully, I'll get around to writing more articles in this format. Less story, more exploring history and current affairs.</p>

							</div>

								
					
