					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/petrograd" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(455145); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=455145&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204947" alt="Petrograd" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=455145)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/petrograd" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(455145); return false;" >Petrograd</a></span> <span class="odate time_1452149106 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">07 Jan 2016 06:45</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2435694">
									

<p>I'm a little iffy on this interpretation. GRU rant:</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>GRU is military intelligence (which did and still does constitute a very large amount of intelligence activity), whereas KGB was&quot;civilian&quot; domestic and foreign intelligence as well as border control. In the breakup of the Soviet Union and forming of the Russian Federation, KGB was gutted and broken into many smaller subgroups including the FSB.</p>
<p>The GRU, on the other hand, didn't get chopped up, still operates, and is a larger intelligence organization than any of the successor groups to the KGB making it the largest intelligence organ in Russia.</p>
<p>So, the logical gap from military intelligence to anomaly acquisition/research/containment is an easy one to make during the Cold War, especially given the idea of parascientific weapons.</p>
<p>Taking it from them and jumping it to their equivalent of the FBI&#8230; I guess that could make sense given the 90's, if it suddenly becomes more important to keep anomalies out of the hands of the mafia and Chechen rebels than getting the edge on the West. Just a bit of a jump.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<br />
Although honestly I assume that this is just because someone early on the site thought GRU sounded cooler than KGB. I'm all for a modern version to play with, I just like thinking it through.
<p>As far as the article goes, I love it. I don't think you've done much beyond gluing together some real world events, making the ending somewhat unsatisfying, but I really enjoy the format and incorporated events.<br />
+1</p>
<p>(Also, I was thinking much the same thing about world events about the Yazidi pilgrimage SCP, but couldn't think of anything interesting our appropriate way to tackle it.)</p>

							</div>

								
